We denote by P the torsor P_{1,k} that we are going to define. At the same time, we will define a trivialisation u_ { \mathrm {B}} \in P_ { \mathrm {B}} of its Betti realisation. Since F^0 \mathbb {Z} (k)_ { \mathrm {DR}} =0, we necessarily have that P_ { \mathrm {DR}} = \mathbb {Z} (k)_ { \mathrm {DR}} = \mathbb {Q}. The Betti structure is
820Equationminus-three-points-3.1.1kminus-three-points-3.1.1k.xml3.1.1kminus-three-points-3.1 \begin {gathered} P_ { \mathrm {B}} = u_ { \mathrm {B}} + (2 \pi i)^k \mathbb {Z} \subset \mathbb {P} _{ { \mathrm {DR}} , \mathbb {C} } = \mathbb {C} \\ \text {with} \quad u_ { \mathrm {B}} = -(k-1)! \zeta (k) \end {gathered} \tag{3.1.1k}
where \zeta is the Riemann \zeta function.

Let \alpha be an N-th root of 1. It defines \alpha \colon \mathbb {Z} {/}N \to \mathbb {Z} {/}N(1) by a \mapsto a \cdot \alpha. We thus obtain \alpha ^{ \otimes (k-1)} \colon \mathbb {Z} {/}N(1) \to \mathbb {Z} {/}N(k). Note that, for \alpha =1, this is the zero map. We denote by \alpha ^{ \otimes (k-1)}T( \alpha ) the \mathbb {Z} {/}N(k)-torsor induced from T( \alpha ) by applying \alpha ^{ \otimes (k-1)}. We have
821Equationminus-three-points-3.1.2kminus-three-points-3.1.2k.xml3.1.2minus-three-points-3.1 P_{ \mathbb {Z} {/}(N)} \coloneqq \sum _{ \alpha ^N=1} \alpha ^{ \otimes (k-1)}T_N( \alpha ). \tag{3.1.2k}
We can equivalently sum over the \alpha \neq1. This definition still makes sense in any algebraic closure \overline {k} of \mathbb {Q}, and the action of \operatorname {Gal} ( \bar { \mathbb {Q} }/ \mathbb {Q} ) is given by transport of structure.

We now define the transition morphisms P_{ \mathbb {Z} {/}(NM)} \to  P_{ \mathbb {Z} {/}(N)}.
We have

822Equationminus-three-points-3.1.3minus-three-points-3.1.3.xml3.1.3minus-three-points-3.1          \prod _{u^M=z} (1-u)         = 1-z       \tag{3.1.3}       

whence, for z \neq0 ,1, we obtain an isomorphism

823Equationminus-three-points-3.1.4minus-three-points-3.1.4.xml3.1.4minus-three-points-3.1         T_N(z)         =  \prod _{u^M=z} T_N(u).       \tag{3.1.4}       

If \beta ^N=1 and \alpha ^M= \beta, then the reduction \mod  N of \alpha \colon \mathbb {Z} {/}NM \to \mathbb {Z} {/}NM(1) is \beta \colon \mathbb {Z} {/}N \to \mathbb {Z} {/}N(1), and that of T_{NM}( \alpha ) is T_N( \alpha ).
From this, we obtain an isomorphism
        \begin {aligned}         P_{ \mathbb {Z} {/}(NM)} \mod  N         &=  \sum _{ \beta ^N=1}  \sum _{ \alpha ^M= \beta }  \alpha ^{ \otimes (k-1)}T_{NM}( \alpha )  \mod  N        \\ &=  \sum _{ \beta ^N=1}  \beta ^{ \otimes (k-1)}  \sum _{ \alpha ^M= \beta } T_N( \alpha )        \\ &=  \sum _{ \beta ^N=1}  \beta ^{ \otimes (k-1)} T_N( \beta )        \\ &= P_{ \mathbb {Z} {/}(N)}.        \end {aligned}     
This defines the desired transition morphism.

If z is not real and \geqslant1, then we have principal determinations
824Equationminus-three-points-3.1.5minus-three-points-3.1.5.xml3.1.5minus-three-points-3.1 \prod _{u^M=z} (1-u)^{1/N} = (1-z)^{1/N} \tag{3.1.5}
as we verify by analytic continuation from z=0, taking into account. It follows from that the \operatorname {comp} _{ \mathbb {Z} {/}(N), { \mathrm {B}} } are compatible with the transition morphisms.

Some preliminaries, before defining \phi _p.
The k-logarithm is defined for |z| \leqslant1 by

826Equationminus-three-points-3.2.1minus-three-points-3.2.1.xml3.2.1minus-three-points-3.2          \ell _k(z)         =  \sum  z^n/n^k.       \tag{3.2.1}       

The \zeta (k) in the formula giving P_ { \mathrm {B}} appears in our approach as the value at 1 of \ell _k.
Let p be a prime number and consider the formal series

827Equationminus-three-points-3.2.2minus-three-points-3.2.2.xml3.2.2minus-three-points-3.2          \ell _k^{(p)}         =  \sum _{p \nmid  n} z^n/n^k.       \tag{3.2.2}       

This is the Taylor series expansion of a rigid analytic function on the projective line over \mathbb {Q} _p with the open disc of radius 1 centred at 1 removed.
Indeed, we have

828Equationminus-three-points-3.2.3minus-three-points-3.2.3.xml3.2.3minus-three-points-3.2          \ell _k^{(p)}(z)         =  \lim _N  \frac {1}{1-z^{p^N}}  \sum _{n=1, p \nmid  n}^{p^N-1} z^n/n^k.       \tag{3.2.3}       

From  we get the identity

829Equationminus-three-points-3.2.4minus-three-points-3.2.4.xml3.2.4minus-three-points-3.2          \ell _k^{(p)}(1/z)         = -(-1)^k \ell _k^{(p)}(z).       \tag{3.2.4}

A formal series calculation gives, for (N,p)=1,

830Equationminus-three-points-3.2.5minus-three-points-3.2.5.xml3.2.5minus-three-points-3.2         N^{k-1} \sum _{u^N=z}  \ell _k^{(p)}(u)         =  \ell _k^{(p)}(z).       \tag{3.2.5}       

This leads us to define the "principal value" at 1

831Equationminus-three-points-3.2.6minus-three-points-3.2.6.xml3.2.6minus-three-points-3.2          \operatorname {vp} \ell _k^{(p)}(1)          \coloneqq   \frac {N^{k-1}}{1-N^{k-1}}  \sum _{ \alpha ^N=1, \alpha \neq1 }  \ell _k^{(p)}( \alpha ).       \tag{3.2.6}       

This number is independent of the choice of N coprime to p.
By , it is zero for k even.

Let M= \mathbb {Z} (k) with k \geqslant1. Let \sigma \in \operatorname {Gal} ( \bar { \mathbb {Q} }/ \mathbb {Q} ) with image c in \widehat { \mathbb {Z}} ^ \times, i.e. \sigma ( \zeta )= \zeta ^c for \zeta a root of unity. can then be written as
843Equationminus-three-points-3.6.2minus-three-points-3.6.2.xml3.6.2minus-three-points-3.6 \sigma p^ \wedge - p^ \wedge = (c^k-1)(p_M)^ \wedge . \tag{3.6.2}
Modulo N, we obtain: let c be an integer coprime to Nn, with \sigma inducing \zeta \mapsto \zeta ^c on the (Nn)-th roots of unity. Then (c^k-1)p_M \in M_ { \mathrm {B}}, and
844Equationminus-three-points-3.6.3minus-three-points-3.6.3.xml3.6.3minus-three-points-3.6 \operatorname {comp} _{ \widehat { \mathbb {Z}} , { \mathrm {B}} }((c^k-1)p_M) \equiv \sigma p^ \wedge - p^ \wedge \mod {N}. \tag{3.6.3}

We will construct an isomorphism of torsors
         Q_{ \mathbb {Z} {/}(N)}         =  \sum   \alpha ^{ \otimes (k-1)}K(- \alpha )_{ \mathbb {Z} {/}(N)}       \tag{3.7.1}       
where the sum is taken over the N-th roots of 1 that are not 1 itself.
